'''Peter David Monteath''' (born 1961) is an Australian historian and academic. He is a professor in Modern European History at [[Flinders University]] in South Australia. Monteath's research interests are in modern European and Australian history. He has a particular interest in prisoners of war, internment, and the German presence in Australia and has written extensively on these subjects.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.flinders.edu.au/people/peter.monteath |title=Peter Monteath |publisher=[[Flinders University]] |date=n.d. |accessdate=2017-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Monteath on Trove Books|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/book/result?q=monteath%2C+peter|website=National Library of Australia|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>

With Jean Fornasiero and John West-Soob, Monteath co-authored ''Encountering Terra Australis: the Australian Voyages of Nicolas Baudin and Matthew Flinders'' (Wakefield Press, 2004), which won the 2004 Frank Broeze Memorial Maritime History Book Prize.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frank Broeze Memorial Maritime History Book Prize|url=http://www.anmm.gov.au/Get-Involved/Grants-and-Awards/History-Prizes#Past-Recipients|website=Australian National Maritime Museum|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>

Monteath co-authored with Valerie Munt ''Red Professor: The Cold War Life of Fred Rose'' (Wakefield Press, 2015), which was shortlisted for the 2016 [[Prime Minister's Prize for Australian History]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Prime Minister's Literary Awards Shortlist|url=http://www.minister.communications.gov.au/mitch_fifield/news/2016_prime_ministers_literary_awards_shortlist_announced#.WUHyLROGNp8|website=Ministers for the Department of Communications and the Arts|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>

